<lesson>

    <slide>
        <text name="text">
            "Building an app has two aspects: Design and Code. The Design defines how it looks and the Code defines how it behaves."
        </text>
        <image name="imageSource">"slide_3_1"</image>
    </slide>

    <slide>
        <text name="text">
            "We’ll start by designing the app on the Design screen and then move on to coding on the Code screen."</text>
        <image name="imageSource">"slide_3_2"</image>
    </slide>

    <slide>
        <text name="text">
            "An app’s design consists of elements called Views, some examples of Views are: Button, TextView and ImageView."
        </text>
        <image name="imageSource">"slide_3_3"</image>
    </slide>

    <slide>
        <text name="text">
            "Most apps consist mainly of Buttons, TextViews and ImageViews
            as you can see in these examples:"
        </text>
        <image name="imageSource">"slide_3_4"</image>
    </slide>

    <slide>
        <text name="text">
            "This is what our app is going to look like. It’s made of a Button and a TextView. We’ll first create a question and then add the rest."
        </text>
        <image name="imageSource">"slide_3_5"</image>
    </slide>

    <slide>
        <text name="text">
            "Every View has a set of properties. Let’s take a look at this Button’s properties."
        </text>
        <image name="imageSource">"slide_3_6"</image>
    </slide>

    <slide>
        <text name="text">"You can control its properties."</text>
        <image name="imageSource">"slide_3_7"</image>
    </slide>

    <slide>
        <text name="text">
            "When you create a new View you should give it a unique and descriptive name - an ID."
        </text>
        <image name="imageSource">"slide_3_8"</image>
    </slide>

